04460nam a22005295i 9780887553271DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19971997xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808875532717 a10.1515/97808875532712doi  a(DE-B1597)664706  a(OCoLC)1412009481  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA 4aBX8141b.I5 1997 7aHEA0410002bisacsh04a392.1200aIn Her Own Voice :bChildbirth Stories from Mennonite Women /ced. by Katherine Martens, Heidi Harms. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[1997] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (246 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tCo-Editor's Note -- tAnna Thiessen -- tMargaret Sawatzky -- tHelen Wedel -- tSara Kroeker -- tMaria Reimer -- tElizabeth Krahn -- tEvelyn Rempel Petkau -- tAnna Fullerton -- tRobyn Epp -- tElsa Neufeld -- tVicki Neufeld -- tGertrude Epp -- tAgatha Martens -- tAgatha Warkentin -- tDi Brandt -- tMarjorie Neufeld Martin -- tMrs.A -- tSusanna Edith Klassen -- tAganetha (Aggie) Klassen -- tPeggy Regehr -- tEdith Parker -- tSue Klassen -- tMagdalene Redekop -- tHlldegard Martens -- tRoberta Loughrin -- tKarin Dirks -- tSelected Sources0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWinnipeg writer Katherine Martens interviewed 26 women from the Mennonite community in southern Manitoba, ranging in age from 22 to 88 years old. They had many different backgrounds, but they all had one important characteristic: all were mothers.In the course of these interviews, Martens was searching for answers to questions that affected her both as a Mennonite and as a woman. How did they feel when they learned of the pregnancy? How did they choose home or hospital birth? How did the traditions of the Mennonite culture affect them as wives and mothers? As they talked, many spoke about the joys and trials of giving birth, and they also told Martens stories about other parts of their lives. Some had escaped the Russian Revolution to emigrate to Canada; others spent their entire lives in rural Manitoba, part of the close-knit Mennonite community, running farms and bearing as many as 15 children. Younger women who had formally left the Mennonite church were still conscious of the impact of the beliefs and customs on their lives.Many women were surprised to be approached for an interview, insisting that they had "no stories to tell." One was visited in a dream by her dead husband, who told her to "leave that alone." Yet, in the privacy of their kitchens and parlours, over sociable cups of tea, many did share with Martens their private fears and joys about what was often seen as a rite of passage into responsible adulthood, and they recalled that childbirth could be a difficult and, at times, traumatic event, but it could also be a radiant and spiritual experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMennonite women. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / Pregnancy & Childbirth.2bisacsh1 aHarms, Heidi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMartens, Katherine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755327140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887553271423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887553271/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles